  "event": {
    "top_event": "Loss of Buoyancy - Well A-1 Dry Tree and Riser Descent",
    "incident_type": "Structural Damage / Equipment Failure",
    "costs": "4700000",
    "actions_taken": [
      "All four dry tree wells and surface controlled subsurface safety valves (SCSSVs) were shut in",
      "All affected areas were barricaded",
      "Personnel mustered",
      "Platform Emergency Shutdown (ESD) and general alarm were initiated",
      "ROVs were dispatched for damage assessment and photography",
      "Inspections performed on other truss spars with same buoyancy can system"
    ],
    "summary": "On December 27, 2017, the Well A-1 riser on the Constitution Spar (GC 680-A) dropped 3-4 feet onto the workover deck grating. On December 31, 2017, during air-up operations on Buoyancy Can Chamber #2, an air leak was detected. The Well A-1 dry tree subsequently descended 28 feet onto the spar deck. Root cause investigation revealed severe corrosion of the air fill-up lines in Chambers #2 and #3, allowing nitrogen to escape and seawater to enter the chambers. Loss of buoyancy in these chambers caused the weight of the dry tree and riser to exceed the buoyancy capacity of the remaining chambers, resulting in structural collapse of the workover deck grating and descent of the wellhead assembly. Estimated damage: $4,700,000.",
    "recommendations": [
      "Houma District issued no specific recommendations to the Regional Office",
      "Inspections both visually and via mini ROVs in the centerwell are being performed on Constitution and three other APC truss spars (Boomvang, Nansen, Gunnison) to ensure no other corrosion problems exist"
    ],
